<percentage>0</percentage></teachingTypeInCurriculum></teachingTypesInCurriculumYear></programCurriculum><programDescriptions><programDescription xml:lang="nl"><![CDATA[Students who have completed this programme will:
understand theories of childhood and the history of the field of children's rights;
understand the implications of children's rights for policy development and implementation;
gain the analytical tools for examining the conditions under which children live how to improve them;
be able to link the field of children's rights to a specific discipline. 

The programme is an interdisciplinary programme in the social sciences leading to a Master of Science (MSc) degree in Social Anthropology and Sociology of Non-Western Societies, Educational Sciences or International Development Studies. 

The curriculum's interdisciplinary character and the students' backgrounds are attractive features of this programme. Connections with the European Network of Masters in Children's Rights provide access to expertise at other universities.

Amsterdam is a city with a history in the development of international relations, commerce and law, and is among the most lively, diverse and cosmopolitan cities in the world. 

